This offering shows up in several searches on what learning is available for those interested in prompt engineering. I was almost half way through and then did some research to make sure I was on the right path. These videos, although numerous in content, do little to actually teach someone to deploy specific types of prompt engineering. There is an actual science behind this as I found out by taking instruction from a major university. There, I was challenged and projects were given and graded--very similar to the college instruction I've received in the past. You will never learn here that there is 20 separate types of prompts and the constructs that go into actually creating a framework for prompt engineering. Would you ever learn that there is a prompt called the Flipped Interaction Pattern? You need to know this kind of knowledge to ever build a career in prompt engineering. The videos here are mostly demo videos and quantity does not make up for quality. You can't learn how to use a ChatGPT application in two or three minutes. I would have chopped this course up into a fourth of what it is and seriously gotten into the various types of prompts. Additionally, I would have given students in-depth instruction on how to use a few of the top apps. Students in prompt engineering are mostly new and not knowing what they need and so rely on the instruction that's available. Choose wisely.

Let me start with this: if you’re looking for the ultimate guide to AI, you might want to keep looking—this course feels more like a buffet where all the dishes are scattered across different rooms, with no rhyme or reason to the layout. Sure, there’s a lot of content here, but the topics are so disjointed you’ll need a GPS and a motivational podcast just to figure out how it all fits together. Spoiler: it doesn’t.

I regret purchasing this course because a lot of the material is outdated, many lectures were recorded over two years ago and do not cover any recent developments in generative AI. I consumed only two chapters plus two videos in Chapter 3 (out of 50 total chapters), and it was immediately clear that the content did not address current tools like Gemini, NotebookLM, Deepseek, or any deep research strategies. Even the Udemy AI chatbot indicated that there is no coverage of automations, deep learning frameworks, or new language models (topics I was hoping to learn about). When I requested a refund through the Purchases tab, I was denied despite having viewed about 4% of the course and having the course for about a week, which, I believe, is against Udemy’s own guideline. This denial feels unjustified, as I wanted to give the course a chance before I through in the towel.

Value for money, this was a superb AI intro course. It offers a very broad and practical introduction to a variety of tools, use cases, projects and to an extraordinary future looking toward Agentic AI and more. The main two instructors are extremely passionate and genuine. The course is quite broad so it is a little uneven pedagogically with short videos, case studies, external videos, but no actual application exercizes to practice the tools. You'll mostly have to do that on your own. I cannot imagine how they can keep this course updated, given how quickly interfaces and tools are changing. I would have preferred a wider and in-depth scope of types of AI in a category and what makes one better (Claude, Chatgpt, Gemini, Perplexity) than the other. But this can change daily. I urge people to stop and try out some of the chapters before moving on as it can get overwhelming. It's nice to know you can go back when you want to deep dive with a tool.

This course is extremely superficial and covers ChatGPT from a marketing and consulting perspective. Many of the lectures are just variations of: "you can ask this of ChatGPT." If you've ever been annoyed by content farms that churn out one blog post after another, this course offers an introduction to the thought processes behind such regurgitation of known facts ad infinitum. I'm giving this one star for multiple reasons. First, this isn't even close to a complete guide. It doesn't cover more advanced topics, like API function calling. I also have significant ideological issues with the bias of the course. It represents much of what is destructive about general AI, such as flooding and spamming. There are many useful and creative ways to use AI, but it's hard to see them when approaching the subject from a marketing consultant's perspective.
